'''Einar Westye Egeberg, Sr.''' (1851 <U+2013> 1940) was a Norwegian businessperson and politician for the [[Conservative Party (Norway)|Conservative Party]].

He was born in [[Oslo|Kristiania]] as a son of Peder Cappelen Egeberg (1810<U+2013>1874) and Hanna Wilhelmine Scheel.<ref name=nbl>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Egeberg, Einar Westye|encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|publisher=Aschehoug|location=Oslo|editor=[[Edvard Bull, Sr.|Bull, Edvard]]; [[Einar Jansen|Jansen, Einar]]|edition=1st|first=S. C.|last=Hammer|authorlink=Simon Christian Hammer|year=1926|volume=3|pages=424<U+2013>425|language=Norwegian}}</ref> He was a brother of [[Ferdinand Julian Egeberg]], first cousin of physician [[Theodor Christian Egeberg]], a grandson of [[Westye Egeberg]] and a nephew of [[Westye Martinus Egeberg]], surgeon [[Christian Egeberg]] and composer [[Fredrikke Egeberg]]. Through his brother he was an uncle of [[Westye Parr Egeberg]], and through a sister he was a granduncle of [[Ferdinand Finne]].<ref name=snl2>{{cite encyclopedia|year=|title=Egeberg|encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]]|editor=|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo|url=http://www.snl.no/Egeberg|language=Norwegian|accessdate=25 February 2011}}</ref>

In September 1877 in [[<U+00D8>stre Aker]] he married Birgitte Halvordine Schou, a daughter of [[Halvor Schou]].<ref name=nbl/> His own daughter Hermine Egeberg was married to [[Lord Chamberlain (Norway)|Lord Chamberlain]] [[Peder Anker Wedel Jarlsberg]].<ref name=snl2/>

He is best known as the co-owner of the family company [[Westye Egeberg & Co]], founded by his grandfather.<ref name=snl2/> He was hired in the company in 1867, and in 1874 he took over the company from his father together with his brother Ferdinand. He acquired burghership in Kristiania in 1882.<ref name=nbl/>

He was a member of the executive committee of Kristiania city council from 1891 to 1894.<ref name=nbl/> He was a deputy representative to the [[Parliament of Norway]] during the term 1892<U+2013>1894, representing the urban constituency ''Kristiania, H<U+00F8>nefoss og Kongsvinger''.<ref name=nsd>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsd.uib.no/polsys/index.cfm?urlname=storting&lan=&MenuItem=N1_1&ChildItem=&State=collapse&UttakNr=33&person=10647|title=Einar Westye Egeberg|publisher=Norwegian Social Science Data Services (NSD)|language=Norwegian|accessdate=25 February 2011}}</ref> He was also a board member of [[Oslo Port Authority|Kristiania Port Authority]], and chaired ''Christiania Handelsstands Forening'' from 1904 to 1908. In 1905 he was declared a lifetime member of the [[International Law Association]].<ref name=nbl/> He was also behind the construction (1899<U+2013>1901) of the [[Egeberg Castle]], which he sold after his wife's death.

